ing their wartime selves. It argues that the Second World War was capable of challenging civilian masculinities, positioning the civilian man below that of the 'soldier hero' while, simultaneously, reinforcing them by bolstering the capacity to provide and to earn high wages, frequently in risky and dangerous work, all which were key markers of masculinity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMasculinityxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMasculinityzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aMenxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMenzGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectsxGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aCivilian Men.  aMasculinities.  aOral History.  aReserved Occupations.  aSecond World War.  aWork.  aWorking Class.  a‘Soldier Hero’.1 aMcIvor, Arthur, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcIvor, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPattinson, Juliette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobb, Linsey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRobb, Linsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610613140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526106131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526106131/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles